To compute $(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a})$, we first expand the expression using the properties of cross products.

Step 1: Using the distributive property of cross products, we can expand the expression as follows:

(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) = 2\mathbf{b} \times (3\mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) - \mathbf{a} \times (3\mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a})

Step 2: Next, we use the distributive property to further expand this expression.

= 2\mathbf{b} \times 3\mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - \mathbf{a} \times 3\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}

Step 3: Since the cross product of any vector with itself is the zero vector, we simplify the expression.

= 6\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 3\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}

Step 4: Now, we substitute the given values of cross products into our expression.

= 6(\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} + 2\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} - 3\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}

Step 5: After substituting the values, we perform scalar multiplication and add the resulting vectors component-wise.

= \frac{1}{6}(6\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} + 2\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ -7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} - 3\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix})

Step 6: Multiplying each component by the scalar, we get

= \begin{pmatrix} 6/6*1+2/6*6-3/6*4 \\ 6/6*-7+2/6*-7-3/6*7 \\ 6/6*18+2/6*3-3/6*2 \end{pmatrix}

Step 7: Adding the corresponding components, we get

= \begin{pmatrix} 2/6*6 \\ -2/6*-84-1/6*7 \\ 11/6*18+1/6*3 \end{pmatrix}

Step 8: Simplifying each component, we get

= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 16 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix}

The answer is \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 16 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix}}.

